<h1 class="hero-h">How to open a <em style="font-family:'Instrument Serif',serif;font-style:italic;color:#00C853;">gym in 2026.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">The 11-step playbook for first-time gym owners. From market research and format selection through financing, buildout, the AI-native tech stack, presale campaign, and grand opening. Built from operator interviews and Treetop's observation across multi-unit fitness engagements.</p>
</div></div>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">The honest framing</span>
<h2 class="h2">Before you start</h2>
<p class="body">Most new gyms fail not because the owner had a bad idea, but because they ran out of cash in months 4-9 before membership reached breakeven. The single best thing a first-time owner can do is take the time to build a realistic working-capital plan <em>before</em> signing a lease, not after.</p>
<p class="body">This playbook is sequenced to surface that reality early: research and financial model come before lease, lease comes before buildout, presale runs in parallel with buildout. Skip steps at your own risk.</p>
<div class="callout"><p><strong>Typical timeline:</strong> 9-15 months for first-time owners. Personal training studios can compress to 4-7 months; full-service gyms often need 12-18 months. See <a href="/how-long-does-it-take-to-open-a-gym" style="color:#00C853;">the full timeline breakdown</a>.</p></div>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Step 1</span>
<h2 class="h2"><span class="step-num">01</span>Market research and format selection</h2>
<p class="body">Before anything else: pick the gym format that matches your market's actual demand and your available capital. The right format for a Tier-3 suburban market is rarely the right format for a Tier-1 urban core.</p>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Drive-time analysis:</strong> Map every competing gym within a 12-minute drive. Note format, price point, hours, member count if knowable.</li>
<li><strong>Demographic fit:</strong> Median household income, age skew, density. CrossFit affiliates work in walkable urban + dense suburban; full-service gyms need population density to support headcount.</li>
<li><strong>Format choices:</strong> Personal training studio · Small boutique · Mid-size group fitness · CrossFit affiliate · Full-service · Boutique franchise. See <a href="/cost-to-start-a-gym" style="color:#00C853;">the cost guide</a> for cost ranges by format.</li>
<li><strong>Honest question to answer:</strong> "Why would a member leave their current gym to come to mine?" If you can't answer in one sentence, the market research is incomplete.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Step 2</span>
<h2 class="h2"><span class="step-num">02</span>Business plan and financial model</h2>
<p class="body">Lenders require one. The act of building one forces you to confront the math.</p>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>36-month financial model:</strong> Month-by-month revenue ramp, fixed and variable costs, breakeven membership count, cash position by month.</li>
<li><strong>Unit economics:</strong> Revenue per member, fully-loaded cost to acquire a member, member lifetime, contribution margin per member-month.</li>
<li><strong>Working capital plan:</strong> 6-12 months of operating expenses funded separately from startup costs. <em>This is the most underbudgeted line item.</em></li>
<li><strong>Sensitivity scenarios:</strong> What happens if presale converts at 60% of plan? At 40%? At 25%? Lenders will ask.</li>
</ul>
<p class="body">Template: <a href="/gym-business-plan" style="color:#00C853;">/gym-business-plan</a>.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Step 3</span>
<h2 class="h2"><span class="step-num">03</span>Secure financing</h2>
<p class="body">Almost no first-time owner self-funds an entire build. Plan for a stacked capital structure:</p>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>SBA 7(a) loan:</strong> Up to $5M, 10-25 year terms, ~10-30% down. 60-120 days to close. Most-common path for first-time gym owners.</li>
<li><strong>Equipment leasing:</strong> 36-60 month terms, low/no money down on equipment. Often layered on top of SBA.</li>
<li><strong>Landlord TI (tenant improvement) allowance:</strong> $20-60/sq ft typical for second-generation retail. Negotiable. Effectively free buildout capital.</li>
<li><strong>Seller financing:</strong> If buying an existing gym, 10-30% of price commonly carried by seller at 6-9% interest.</li>
<li><strong>Friends and family / ROBS / personal capital:</strong> The required equity stake.</li>
</ul>
<p class="body">Full breakdown: <a href="/how-to-finance-a-gym" style="color:#00C853;">/how-to-finance-a-gym</a>.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Step 4</span>
<h2 class="h2"><span class="step-num">04</span>Form the legal entity</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>LLC vs S-Corp:</strong> Most single-location gyms form as LLCs taxed as S-Corps. Ask your CPA.</li>
<li><strong>EIN, state registration, business bank account, business credit card.</strong></li>
<li><strong>Insurance binders:</strong> General liability, professional liability, workers comp, property. Required before lease execution.</li>
<li><strong>Music licensing accounts:</strong> ASCAP + BMI + SESAC. ~$1K-$4K/year per a typical gym.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Step 5</span>
<h2 class="h2"><span class="step-num">05</span>Site selection and lease negotiation</h2>
<p class="body">Location is the single biggest determinant of long-term success. Spend the time.</p>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Drive-time/walk-time:</strong> 80% of members live or work within 12 minutes of the gym. Visibility from a major road helps but isn't required.</li>
<li><strong>Anchor co-tenants:</strong> Grocery, Target, Whole Foods, coffee, daycare. These pull recurring foot traffic past your door.</li>
<li><strong>Parking ratio:</strong> 1 space per 200 sq ft minimum for most formats; more for full-service gyms with peak-hour crowding.</li>
<li><strong>Lease terms:</strong> 5+5 or 10-year primary; TI allowance; rent abatement during buildout (4-6 months typical); CAM caps; personal guarantee scope (cap it if possible).</li>
<li><strong>Demographic fit:</strong> Use Esri Tapestry or SimplyAnalytics on the trade area before signing.</li>
</ul>
<div class="callout"><p><strong>The trap:</strong> Cheap rent in the wrong location is the most-expensive lease you can sign. A 30% rent premium for the right co-tenants and demographic mix usually pays back 3-5x in member acquisition cost.</p></div>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Step 6</span>
<h2 class="h2"><span class="step-num">06</span>Permits and buildout</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Building permit:</strong> 30-90 day approval window typical. Slow markets (SF, NYC, Boston) can run 4-6 months.</li>
<li><strong>Contractor selection:</strong> Get three bids. Reference-check the last two gym projects each has done. Fixed-price contract with milestone draws.</li>
<li><strong>Construction window:</strong> 60-150 days for most second-generation retail. Ground-up construction is 9-18 months and rarely worth it for a first gym.</li>
<li><strong>Critical-path items:</strong> HVAC sizing (sweat + odor + heat from cardio is real), flooring (rubber spec matters), electrical for cardio + sound, locker room plumbing, ADA compliance.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Step 7</span>
<h2 class="h2"><span class="step-num">07</span>Equipment procurement and install</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Buy vs lease decision:</strong> Lease cardio (depreciates fast, breaks); buy strength + functional (holds value, rarely breaks).</li>
<li><strong>Used vs new:</strong> Auctions and gym closures can yield 40-60% off retail on commercial-grade strength equipment.</li>
<li><strong>Vendor diversification:</strong> Don't tie 100% of equipment to a single vendor, service responsiveness varies, and lock-in pricing hurts later.</li>
<li><strong>Install scheduling:</strong> Equipment arrives 6-12 weeks after order. Schedule install to land 7-10 days before soft open.</li>
</ul>
<p class="body">Decision framework: <a href="/should-i-buy-or-lease-gym-equipment" style="color:#00C853;">/should-i-buy-or-lease-gym-equipment</a>.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Step 8</span>
<h2 class="h2"><span class="step-num">08</span>Tech stack: CRM and AI agents</h2>
<p class="body">This is the category where 2026 is meaningfully different. The legacy gym software stack used to require $8K-$20K/year in software fees plus 1-2 admin staff. AI agent platforms collapse much of that into a single subscription.</p>
<h3 class="h3">Minimum viable tech stack (2026)</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Gym CRM as system of record:</strong> MindBody, Glofox, Pike13, Zen Planner. $2K-$5K/year.</li>
<li><strong>AI agent platform:</strong> Handles lead nurture, no-show recovery, member retention, member coaching. $3K-$12K/year for a small gym. Purpose-built leader: <a href="https://fitagentic.ai" style="color:#00C853;">fitagentic.ai</a>.</li>
<li><strong>Payments:</strong> Stripe or Square (often integrated with CRM).</li>
<li><strong>Member-facing app:</strong> Usually included with CRM or AI platform.</li>
</ul>
<div class="callout"><p><strong>The hidden savings:</strong> AI agents handling lead nurture + no-show recovery + member-facing coaching often eliminate 1-2 front-desk/membership-consultant hires entirely. That's $40K-$80K per avoided hire in year one, usually the difference between surviving and not.</p></div>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Step 9</span>
<h2 class="h2"><span class="step-num">09</span>Hire and certify staff</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Lean opening team:</strong> Owner-operator + 1-2 trainers + 1-2 coaches. Hire the GM later if needed.</li>
<li><strong>Role design:</strong> Avoid the "front desk + everything else" job description. AI agents now handle most of "everything else."</li>
<li><strong>Certifications:</strong> NASM, NSCA, ACE for personal training. CrossFit Level 1 for affiliates. Bookend with CPR/AED requirement.</li>
<li><strong>Payroll setup:</strong> Gusto or Justworks for a small team; ADP if scaling fast.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Step 10</span>
<h2 class="h2"><span class="step-num">10</span>Run the 90-day presale</h2>
<p class="body">The single highest-leverage activity in the entire opening sequence. Presale memberships pay for the working-capital months that follow. Skip or underinvest in presale and you'll spend the next 12 months catching up.</p>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Founding-member offer:</strong> Locked-in lifetime rate at 60-70% of grand-open price. Cap the cohort.</li>
<li><strong>Channel mix:</strong> Local Meta ads, Google Local, walk-by signage at the buildout site, partnerships with adjacent businesses, referral program.</li>
<li><strong>Conversion benchmark:</strong> 30-50% of qualified leads should convert during presale. Below 25% means offer or pricing is off.</li>
<li><strong>AI agent role:</strong> Lead nurture sequences, no-show recovery for tours, presale-member onboarding before the doors open.</li>
</ul>
<p class="body">Full playbook: <a href="/gym-pre-sale-playbook" style="color:#00C853;">/gym-pre-sale-playbook</a>.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Step 11</span>
<h2 class="h2"><span class="step-num">11</span>Soft open, then grand open</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Soft open:</strong> 7-14 days with founding members only. Stress-test class scheduling, check-in flow, payment processing, locker rooms, cleaning cadence. Fix everything.</li>
<li><strong>Grand open:</strong> Public launch with full marketing push, opening event, press coverage if relevant.</li>
<li><strong>First 90 days post-open:</strong> Daily standups on member onboarding, churn signals, NPS. The first 30 days of a new member's experience predict their 12-month retention more than anything else that follows.</li>
</ul>
<div class="callout"><p><strong>The post-open mistake:</strong> Most owners treat grand open as the finish line. It's not, it's the starting line of the working-capital survival window. Months 4-9 post-open are where most failures happen.</p></div>
</div></section>

